The locust years of Latin America
The bad news continues to accumulate these days in Latin America.
Economic conditions are worsening almost everywhere, social cohesion is eroding, and political instability is growing.
It is not surprising given that the vast majority of Latin American countries have been going nowhere over the past twenty years.
Capital was sold off and national debts disproportionately increased, but nothing lasting and beneficial was achieved.
These years have really been devoured by the locusts.
Over the past 20 years, annual per capita GDP growth in Latin America has averaged 0.35%.
At this rate, an economy would take 200 years to double.
In Asia, the standard of living doubles every decade.
With such anemic growth, how can Latin America hope to compete in world trade except through a meager wage increase?
Economic stagnation stems from poor governance, not bad luck.
If Latin America does not change, it may start to resemble Africa more and more - a region composed of weak states with large informal economies and widespread poverty.
Four factors have placed it on this path.
First, in the rush to privatization, everything from public services to processing industries was put up for auction.
For a brief time, the sales of capital helped balance national budgets and also provided resources to support consumption.
Finally, the revenues derived from privatization have produced little in terms of better infrastructure or more competitive exports.
Worse still, the liquidation of state assets was accompanied by massive external borrowing.
In some cases, particularly in Argentina, the borrowing undertaken by national buyers exhausted all available credit ranges.
Other countries have not reached Argentina's level, but solvency represents a problem in virtually all Latin American countries.
Secondly, given that reform has not brought prosperity, the region has become disillusioned.
The influx of capital produced an effect of wealth, but only as long as it existed.
When the money stopped flowing, the wealth dried up.
No sensible politician would commit to another decade of structural reforms that would push the patience of average Latin Americans beyond the limits of electoral survival.
But without a greater number of deep reforms, too few preconditions for economic growth will be met to attract investments, without which no growth is possible.
This development dilemma announces the third factor: incompetent policies.
The governments that operated according to technocratic lines and considered economic growth as a rising tide lifting all boats are gone.
In Argentina, inept presidents succeed one another.
Institutions are dismantled, property rights are questioned, and a corrupt and random redistribution effort is underway.
Peru and Venezuela are not much luckier; Brazil may soon follow the same path.
The popularity of Lula Ignacia da Silva and his team, who lead opinion polls in the period preceding Brazil's presidential elections, suggests that a large part of the Latin American population is prepared to reject traditional governments.
Lula and his party are so far from the dominant economic thinking and politics that capital is already fleeing - even though the elections are still several months away.
In Mexico, democratization has brought greater stability, but this could well prove ephemeral.
The peso is now excessively overvalued.
If the current account balance continues to deteriorate, the economy risks a hard landing.
Regarding all the good news about Mexico's budding democracy, its president is starting to justify the fears that existed about him: no vision, no Congress, and no team knowing what it has to do.
The last factor concerns the desperately low savings rate that is endemic to the Americas.
Indeed, this is the economically sound financial result because where there is little savings, there is little investment - and little foundation for accumulating capital and boosting productivity.
Venezuela now yearns for the fat years of OPEC in the 1970s — years to which it did not contribute, having neglected to develop its oil industry.
The wealth of Argentina is now taking vacations in Miami, perhaps forever.
Brazil and Mexico are perfect examples of countries that sold their assets and borrowed rather than save.
The contrast with Asia is striking.
Take China, where savings and investment rates reach nearly 40%, where the current account is in surplus, and where there is no public debt.
Government institutions favor the market, and the population is well-educated, disciplined, and flexible in learning.
The rewards for taking risks and initiative are immediate and strongly motivating.
One cannot deny that China remains a poor country.
Its per capita GDP represents only half of Brazil's.
But with a growth rate in China's coastal region at around 15% annually, can it seriously be doubted that within the next 15 years it will surpass Brazil?
In China, despite all the enormous problems encountered, things continue to proceed correctly, firstly due to the massive flow of foreign direct investments and the imminent benefits of joining the WTO.
In Latin America, things continue to deteriorate: governments backtrack on reform and the economy loses ground compared to the rest of the world.
Latin America was doing well when untapped funds were flowing in, but those times are largely over.
We must therefore anticipate much worse economic, social, and political conditions in the years to come.
Demagogues such as Hugo Chavez in Venezuela or Carlos Menem — an Argentine presidential candidate once again — may seem like a bad joke, but anyone concerned about the fate of Latin America should not laugh.
